<TITLE>hypxcs</TITLE><h3><center><font color=#brown >Command HYPXSC</h3></center></font><hr> The command HYPXCS allows you to calculate  hyperfine-resolved integral cross sections for collisions of spherical atoms with diatomic molecules in <sup>1</sup>&Sigma;, <sup>2</sup>&Sigma;, and <sup>2</sup>&Pi;  electronic states.  These integral cross sections are outputted   to the file <tt>{jobname}n.hfx</tt> where <tt>n</tt> is the cardinal value of the energy (see below).  The hyperfine-resolved cross sections are tabulated in columns as <tt><ul> Energy j<sub>i</sub> in<sub>i</sub> F<sub>i</sub> j<sub>f</sub> in<sub>f</sub> F<sub>f</sub> sigma</ul></tt> This command also creates the file <tt>{jobname}n.xms</tt>   which contains integral cross sections without hyperfine resolution tabulated in columns as <tt><ul> Energy j<sub>i</sub> in<sub>i</sub> j<sub>f</sub> in<sub>f</sub> sigma</ul></tt>This is similar to the fort.7 file created in MOLSCAT<p> The command line syntax is<tt><ul>          HYPXSC,{jobname},nucspin,ienerg</tt></ul> where<ul>      <tt>{jobnam}:</tt>&#160; the jobname under which the integral cross sections                  have been stored as <tt>{jobname}n.ics</tt> and, furthermore, under which                 the S-matrices have been stored as <tt>{jobname}n.smt</tt>.  Here <tt>n</tt> denotes the                  value of the parameter <tt>ienerg</tt> (see below). <p>                                   Integral                  cross section (.ics) files can be generated by setting                  the flag <a href=prxsec.html><tt>WRXSEC</tt></a> = .true.  The S-matrix files can be generated                 by setting the flag <a href=wrsmat.html><tt> WRSMAT</tt> </a>= .true.  The default value                  of <tt>{jobnam}</tt> is set by the instruction <ul><tt>JOB ={jobname}</ul></tt><p>                                  <img src=cautionsmall.gif>                 Note that for full close-coupling calculations                 it is necessary to carry out calculationsfor both values of the parity (this is ensured by setting <tt><a href="jlpar.html">JLPAR</a>=0</tt>; see the <a href=jlpar.html>JLPAR</a> page for more information)<p>If no value of <tt>{jobnam}</tt>has been set, thedefault value of                   <tt>{jobname}</tt> is <tt>Job</tt><p>     <tt>nucspin:</tt>&#160;The total nuclear spin I of the diatomic molecule<p>                             <tt>ienerg:</tt>&#160; The cardinal value of the energy for which the integral cross                 sections are to be computed. <i>i. e.</i> if ienerg = 2, then the                 second energy <i>S</i> matrix file <tt>{jobname}2.smt</tt> or second energy                 integral cross section file <tt>{jobname}2.ics</tt> are used.  The                 default value of inerg is 1</ul><hr><img src=warning.gif> At present, the command <tt> HYPXSC</tt> is operational only for collisions of sphericalatoms with diatomic molecules in <sup>1</sup> 	&Sigma;, <sup>2</sup>&Sigma;, and <sup>2</sup>&Pi; electronic states (<a href=basis.html><tt>BASISTYP</tt></a> = 1, 2, or 3).<hr>Go to:<center><br><a href=commands.html>Commands</a> | <!-- <a href=intcrs.ex.html> An example of this command | <a href=examples.html>Examples</a>  -->| <a href=hibhelp.html>Hibridon Help</a><br></center>